40|$|Bringing {{together}} {{the concepts of}} <b>design</b> <b>control</b> and reliability engineering, this book is a must for medical device manufacturers. It helps them {{meet the challenge of}} designing and developing products that meet or exceed customer expectations and also meet regulatory requirements. Part One covers motivation for <b>design</b> <b>control</b> and validation, <b>design</b> <b>control</b> requirements, process validation and design transfer, quality system for <b>design</b> <b>control,</b> and measuring <b>design</b> <b>control</b> program effectiveness. Part Two discusses risk analysis and FMEA, designing-in reliability, reliability and design verifi...|$|R
2500|$|On {{the first}} half of the 1980s, Prof. Fang and his team {{organized}} almost one hundred noise control pilot study in 13 provinces and 40 enterprises with the support of relevant departments of the State Council in order to provide the basis for developing noise standard. This large-scale engineering practice not only provided a paradigm for the implementation of noise <b>control</b> <b>design,</b> but also verified the fact that the vast majority of industrial enterprises verification could achieve the noise limit through efforts. These examples were included in the book named as [...] "114 cases of Noise Control" [...] (in Chinese). The specifications, which were studied and drawn up by almost the whole noise industry and related industry, were approved and promulgated by the Ministry of National Planning Commission in December 1985, named as Chinese national standards GBJ 87-1985 [...] "Industrial Enterprises Noise <b>Control</b> <b>Design</b> Specifications". The approval and promulgation of the specifications marked the birth of Noise Control Engineering in China. From then on, noise was not only of physics or acoustics, but also a subject area of engineering and industrial field.|$|E
2500|$|During {{this time}} Tsien wrote Engineering Cybernetics which was {{published}} by McGraw Hill in 1954. The book deals with the practice of stabilizing servomechanisms. In its 18 chapters it considers non-interacting controls of many-variable systems, <b>control</b> <b>design</b> by perturbation theory, and von Neumann’s theory of error control (chapter 18). Ezra Krendel reviewed the book, stating that it is [...] "difficult to overstate the value of Tsien's book to those interested in the overall theory of complex control systems." [...] Evidently Tsien’s approach is primarily practical, as Kendel notes that for servomechanisms the [...] "usual linear design criterion of stability is inadequate and other criteria arising from the physics of the problem must be used." ...|$|E
2500|$|Cognitive {{impairments}} {{are present}} even after {{an individual has}} been awake for approximately 17 hours; in fact, {{recent studies have shown}} that these decrements are similar to those that result from an elevated blood alcohol level. A compelling [...] laboratory study from Williamson and Feyer [...] used a cross-over randomized <b>control</b> <b>design</b> to observe cognitive and motor performance after minor sleep deprivation to performance after alcohol consumption. All subjects participated in both alcohol consumption and sleep deprivation, and the order of testing was counterbalanced so that half of the subjects participated in the alcohol consumption part first while the other half participated in the sleep deprivation part first. To avoid carry-over effects from one condition to the next, subjects were provided with a night of rest in a motel between each condition.|$|E
